revisions.rev:
'''Eliminationism''' is the belief that one's political opponents are not just wrongheaded, misinformed or even acting in bad faith but that they are a cancer on the [[body politic]] that must be excised — either by separation from the public at large, through [[censorship]] or by outright [[extermination]] — in order to protect the purity of the nation.<ref name="Holland 2009">{{cite paper| last = Holland | first = Joshua | title = The Terrorist Threat: Right-Wing Radicals and the Eliminationist Mindset | date = June 12, 2009 | url = http://www.alternet.org/module/printversion/140578 | accessdate = 2009-07-24}}</ref>
The 1996 history book ''[[Hitler's Willing Executioners]]'' by [[Daniel Goldhagen]] posits that ordinary [[Germans]] not only knew about, but also supported, the [[Holocaust]] because of a unique and virulent "[[eliminationist antisemitism]]" in the German identity, which had developed in the preceding centuries.
